<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix</i> <i>petrophila</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the dwarf shrub and herbaceous layers with <i>Antennaria</i> <i>media</i>, <i>Calamagrostis</i> <i>muiriana</i>, <i>Castilleja</i> <i>lemmonii</i>, <i>Gentiana</i> <i>newberryi</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>parryi</i>, <i>Kalmia</i> <i>microphylla</i>, <i>Luzula</i> <i>comosa</i>, <i>Oreostemma</i> <i>alpigenum</i>, <i>Phyllodoce</i> <i>breweri</i>, <i>Potentilla</i> <i>drummondii</i>, <i>Salix</i> <i>orestera</i>, <i>Trisetum</i> <i>spicatum</i> and <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>cespitosum</i>. Emergent trees may be present as krummholz at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>albicaulis</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 50 cm (1 m); canopy is intermittent
to continuous. Herbs are approximately the same height as the woody species. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Salix petrophila</i> > 5% absolute cover in the shrub layer with tallest dominant plants < 5 m (Potter 2005).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Subalpine to alpine sites where snow lingers into the summer in lee of cliffs and boulders, secondary slopes, and cirques. Soils are thin and rocky, primarily loams mixed with occasional sands and organic materials. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Salix petrophila</i> as an FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
