<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix petrophila </i>is a dwarf, prostrate shrub that is less than 10 cm high. Leaves are glaucous below and glabrous to hairy with sparse, long, silky hairs, and upper sides are green. Plants form colonies by layering. Stems are decumbent, prostrate, or erect. The erect catkins are up to 15 cm. <i>S. petrophila </i>is included in <i>S. arctica </i>in <i>The Jepson Manual </i>(Hickman 1993) and other botanical literature, but Argus (1997) now considers populations in California and elsewhere to be <i>S. petrophila</i>. <i>S. arctica </i>grows across Canada south to California and is circumpolar; <i>S. petrophila </i>occurs in the Rocky Mountains as far north as British Columbia and south to California, though the geographical boundary between these two species is uncertain. <br/>
<br/>
We know little about the relationship of this alliance and other vegetation types at high elevations in the Sierra Nevada. Ratliffâ€™s (1982) gentian-aster meadow type with high cover of <i>Vaccinium cespitosum </i>somewhat resembles this alliance. He speculated that this willow alliance represented disturbed areas in <i>Calamagrostis muiriana </i>meadows. Potter (2005) suggested that all of these may be variations of the same alliance or association, distinguished by differences in stand history or spatial relationships. The higher shrub cover and presence of diagnostic species such as <i>S. petrophila </i>is suggestive of a distinct alliance (Sawyer and Keeler- Wolf 2007). Associations of <i>Salix petrophila </i>occur throughout the high mountains of the Rocky Mountains beyond the range of <i>Calamagrostis muiriana </i>(Viereck et al. 1992). The <i>Salix nivalis </i>alliance is also related to this alliance; we need more sampling and analysis to determine fully their relationships. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
