    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ek, Eo). Stands occur in subalpine meadows and mesic alpine slopes throughout the central and southern Sierra Nevada from the Lake Tahoe Basin to southern Tulare Co. (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Most inventories are from the central and southern part of the range at Harvey Monroe Hall RNA (Taylor 1984, see Cheng 2004), in the Convict Creek drainage (Pemble 1970), in the Carson Pass area (Major and Taylor 1977), in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), and generally in the section (Potter 2005). They are similar to stands of the <i>Calamagrostis muiriana</i> alliance except that they tend to have high cover of <i>Salix petrophila.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dm). Stands and individuals of <i>S. petrophila</i> exist on the upper slopes of Lassen Peak.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The rooting and spreading habit tends to stabilize moist turf in meadows and stream borders in late snowmelt areas. Most stands are well above current livestock use, though they were grazed 100 years ago. Today, recreational activities and trails impact some stands. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
